==English==

===Etymology===
French ''[[théorie]]'', from Latin ''[[theoria]]'', from Greek ''[[θεωρία]]''.

===Noun===
'''theory''' (''plural:'' '''theories''')

# An [[unproven]] [[conjecture]].
#: ''I have a '''theory''' about who broke into the school last night, but it's just a '''theory'''.''
# An [[expectation]] of what [[should]] [[happen]], [[barring]] [[unforeseen]] [[circumstances]].
#: ''So we'll be there in three hours?'' - ''That's the '''theory'''.''
# (''science'')  A [[coherent]] [[statement]] or set of statements that [[attempt]]s to [[explain]] [[observe]]d [[phenomenon|phenomena]], and which has [[testable]] [[implication]]s.
#: ''There is now a well-developed '''theory''' of electrical charge.''
# (''mathematics, uncountable'') A [[field]] of [[study]] attempting to [[exhaustive]]ly [[describe]] a particular [[class]] of [[construct]]s. <!-- Not quite broad enough to include "music theory".  Where do we put that? -->
#: ''Knot '''theory''' classifies the mappings of a circle into 3-space.''
# (''logic'') A [[set]] of [[axiom]]s, together with all [[statement]]s [[derivable]] from them.
#: ''A '''theory''' is consistent if it has a model.''

